{{italic title}} {|{{Infobox Ship Begin}} {{Infobox Ship Image |Ship image=[[Image:Firefighter-nhl.JPG|200px]] |Ship caption=The fireboat ''Fire Fighter'' }} {{Infobox Ship Career |Hide header= |Ship country=[[New York City Fire Department]] |Ship flag=[[Image:Flag of New York City.svg|60px|Flag of the City of New York]] |Ship name=Marine 9 ''Fire Fighter'' |Ship operator=[[New York City Fire Department]] |Ship ordered= |Ship awarded= |Ship builder=United Shipyards |Ship yard number=856 |Ship laid down= |Ship launched=August 26, 1938 |Ship sponsor= |Ship christened= |Ship completed= |Ship acquired= |Ship commissioned= |Ship recommissioned= |Ship decommissioned= |Ship in service= |Ship out of service= |Ship renamed= |Ship reclassified= |Ship refit= |Ship struck= |Ship reinstated= |Ship homeport= [[Staten Island]], [[New York|NY]] |Ship motto= |Ship nickname= |Ship honours= |Ship honors= |Ship captured= |Ship fate= |Ship status= |Ship notes= |Ship badge= }} {{Infobox Ship Characteristics |Hide header= |Header caption= |Ship class= |Ship tonnage=220.44 net |Ship displacement= |Ship tons burthen= |Ship length={{convert|134|ft|m|abbr=on}} |Ship beam={{convert|32|ft|m|abbr=on}} |Ship height={{convert|25|ft|m|abbr=on}} |Ship draught={{convert|9.24|ft|m|abbr=on}} |Ship draft={{convert|9|ft|m|abbr=on}} |Ship hold depth= |Ship ice class= |Ship sail plan= |Ship power= |Ship propulsion=Twin 1500 hp, 16-cylinder, 3968 CID General Motors Winton diesel engines |Ship speed=15mph |Ship range= |Ship endurance= |Ship test depth= |Ship boats= |Ship capacity= |Ship complement= |Ship crew=7 |Ship time to activate= |Ship troops= |Ship sensors= |Ship EW= |Ship armament= |Ship armour= |Ship armor= |Ship aircraft= |Ship aircraft facilities= |Ship notes= }} {{Infobox nrhp | embed = yes | name = ''Firefighter'' (fireboat) | nrhp_type = nhl | image = | caption = | locmapin=New York City | location = | nearest_city = | lat_degrees = | long_degrees = | coord_parameters = region:US-NY_type:landmark | area = | built = 1938 | architect = William Francis Gibbs | architecture = | designated_nrhp_type = June 30, 1989<ref name="nhlsum"/> | added = June 30, 1989<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref> | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | refnum=89001447 | mpsub = | governing_body = [[New York City Fire Department]] }} |} '''''Fire Fighter''''', also known as '''''Firefighter''''', is a fireboat serving the [[New York City Fire Department]]. She was an active fireboat serving as Marine Company 9 until being retired in 2010. She was the most powerful diesel-electric [[fireboat]] when built in 1938. She has fought more than 50 fires, including upon the [[SS Normandie|SS ''Normandie'']] in 1942.<ref name="nrhpinv"/>
Other well known fires she participated in include the [[SS El Estero|SS ''El Estero'']] in 1943, and the fire following the collision of ''[[Esso Brussels]]'' and [[Sea Witch (container ship)|SS ''Sea Witch'']] in 1973. On [[September 11, 2001]], ''Fire Fighter'', along with the rest of the FDNY Marine units and the ''[[John J. Harvey (fireboat)|John J. Harvey]]'', a retired fireboat being restored by volunteers, were in active service pumping water from the Hudson River into [[Ground Zero]] when the water mains failed.<ref name="groundzero">{{cite news | url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0BQK/is_6_7/ai_94509618 | title = Fireboats: few & far between | publisher = Boat/US Magazine | accessdate = 2008-03-14 | first=Ryck | last=Lydecker | year=2002 }}</ref>
The boat, as ''Firefighter'', was declared a U.S. [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1989.<ref name="nhlsum">{{cite web|url=http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=2075&ResourceType=Structure |title=Firefighter (Fireboat)|date=2007-09-14|work=National Historic Landmark summary listing|publisher=National Park Service}}</ref><ref name="nrhpinv">{{Cite document|title={{PDFlink|[http://pdfhost.focus.nps.gov/docs/NHLS/Text/89001447.pdf National Register of Historic Places Registration: Firefighter]|461&nbsp;KB}}|author=James P. Delgado|date=January 20, 1989|publisher=National Park Service|postscript=<!--None-->}} and {{PDFlink|[http://pdfhost.focus.nps.gov/docs/NHLS/Photos/89001447.pdf ''Accompanying 8 photos from 1939, 1942, and 1988'']|1.26&nbsp;MB}}</ref>
''Fire Fighter'' was retired in 2010, and replaced by the fireboat ''[[Fire Fighter II]]''.<ref>[http://nyfd.com/calderoneA/lerch17.html NYFD.com]</ref>
